LINUX: basics, not admin level
-----------------------------

Absolute path:
providing clear path from the beginning 
Ex: cd /c/prgmfiles/....

Relative path:
providing path from current directory
Ex: cd /opt/file1


COPY a FILE:
cp src dest

COPY a DIRECTORY:
cp -r src dest

CUT PASTE:
mv src dest

another way for/to use mv command:
mv old name .... used to rename files or directories also
ex: mv mohan git or mv test1 dir1

PERMISSIONS:

files or directories::
r = read = 4
w = write = 2
x = execution = 1

Users | Group | Others
rwx      rwx      rwx

umask:
(how to check, cmd is umask.)
we won't be changing but can be changed using cmd, umask xxx

dir:

 777  (full permissions)
-022  (Umask value) 
-----
= 755  (means defualt: drwxrx-rx(for direc))

file:

666 (file doesn't have exec persmissions)


 666
-022
-----
= 644 (means default: rw-r--r-- )


ex: chmod 777 dir/file
Example: 
give the permissions to, file1 --> rwxrw-r--
what is the syntax??

Ans: chmod 764 file1

for whole directory and all files same permission:
cmd:: chmod -R 777/764/....



Installations on Linux:
yum is repo may having mostly all standard packages.
Linux before 5 or 6 doesn't have yum. we have to install yum seperately

ex:
yum install git -y
or 
to check:: rpm -qa git


Cmd for generating key in terminal::
ssh -keygen


process check:
cmd... ps -ef

create users:
cmd.. useradd username, ex: useradd prasad
psswd: cmd.. passwd xxxx, ex: passwd prasadabc

delete user: dletes only user, won't delete directory or group
userdel username... ex: userdel xxxx

Note:
1. Whenever we delete user, Group associated with User gets deleted
2. Whenever we create a User, Group gets created.
how to delete user's home dir

to delete User's home dir:
cmd.. userfel -r username.. ex: userdel -r xxx

how to add/delete user's group
1. cat/etc/group   
2. Adding Group:  groupadd groupX
3. Adding user to a Grp: usermod -aG groupX usernamexxx
4. Deleting Grp: groupdel groupX 


USER MANAGEMENT:
how to check/list users & attributes::
-------------------------------------
cmd.. cat/etc/passwd
ex: prasad:x:1000:1000::/home/prasad:/bin/bash
this is called user stanza
references:
prasad... username
x........ password feild
1000..... userID 
1000..... GroupID
::....... Comment msg
/home.... home dir
/prasad.. user dir
/bin..... shell dir
/bash.... shell dir

how to change attributes:
-------------------------
1. cat/etc/passwd
2. ex: home dir change... usermod -d "/opt/dir1" userX
       shell dir change... usermod -s "/bin/sh" userX
       comment msg change.. usermod -c "Test-user" userX
3. changing at a time:
  ex: usermod -c "cloud-user" -d "/home/userX" -s "/bin/bash" usrX


how to provide multiple attributes while creating user:
-------------------------------------------
lets say, reqmnts: /bin/sh, test-user2, /opt/test

ex: useradd userXYX -s "/bin/sh" -c "Test-userXYZ" -d "/opt/test
then,
cat/etc/passwd
check for the user details/attributes created for userXYZ.


Qstn:
password change for user assigned. how to change?

ans: passwd usernamexxx, it will ask, you can setup the passwrd

or admin/root has to change. it comes in Ansible going farward.



ps -ef:
------
listing the process

GREP: Global Reglr Exprssns,
And it is a case senssitive | to ignore use -i
---------------------------
It is like a fitler and can list as per our reqmnts.

ex:
ps -ef | grep
gives the output of ps -ef and connects to grep like a filter

ps -ef | grep xxxx ... given info of xxxx from all ps
or
grep add git.. gives info of 'add' from 'Git' file
or
grep "config" git.. gives and o/p of config from git
or 
ex: grep "prasad" /etc/prasad
ex: ps -ef | grep prasad

to get word count (wc): ex: wc filenamexxx, ex: wc git.....
---------------------------------------------------------
to get only lines (l) :  ex wc -l git
---------------------------------------------
to get lines with word (l): ex: wc -lw git
-------------------------------------------------------
to get word with character (wc): ex: wc -wc git
---------------------------------------------------
displaying fornmt: lines words letters
-------------------------------------------------
ex: ps -ef | grep prasaf | wc
-------------------------------

kill a process: kill -9 pid (pid-process id)
ex: kill -9 xxxx
--------------------

switching to users: su - xxxx .....ex: su - devops or su - prasad
-note: only root user can switch to any users,
       when a normal user swtichs to into other user it prompts & 	asks a passwrd.

- if you dont mention any user, ex: su, it takes to root.
